Activist Fund Hudson Executive Capital is About To Make Another Investment









Armie Margaret Lee




Jun 6, 2016 2:43 PM EDT













 












































































 Since its founding last year, activist investor Hudson Executive Capital LP has received 16 inbound opportunities from publicly traded companies  seeking its investment, according to James C. Woolery, Hudson Executive's co-founder and managing partner, during the  The Deal's Corporate Governance 2016 conference on Monday.   Of the 16, Hudson Executive has invested in one and is about to invest in another, said Woolery. He did not name the companies.   Those companies are separate from Hudson Executive's investments that have been previously disclosed, including CIT Group ( CIT) , Comerica  ( CMA) and WhiteWave Foods ( WWAV) .   WhiteWave is a holding in Jim Cramer's Action Alerts PLUS Charitable Trust Portfolio. Want to be alerted before CLearn more now.ramer buys or sells WWAV? Learn more now.   New York-based Hudson Executive was formed last year by Wall Street veterans Woolery and Douglas Braunstein. They have  assembled a stable of current and former CEOs, together with a senior adviser for governance and regulatory matters, to serve on the firm's advisory board.   Woolery, whose firm does not engage in proxy battles, told conference attendees at the JW Marriott Essex House in New York City on Monday that we're moving to a post-proxy fight world.   While there will still be proxy fights brought about by other activist firms, Woolery thinks that shareholders "have a lot of soft power away from proxy fights. They're going to exercise it in an increasingly active way."   That's the world we're heading toward, he said, adding that we're in the early innings of that.   Woolery was on a panel called "How the Engagement between Traditional Long-Only Funds, Activist Investors, Companies and Shareholders is Changing," that included Steven R. Walker, general counsel and managing director, board advisory services at National Association of Corporate Directors; Zach Oleksiuk, head of Americas corporate governance and responsible investment at BlackRock ( BLK) ; Clifton S. Robbins, CEO at of Blue Harbour Group; and Anne Sheehan, director of corporate governance at the California State Teachers' Retirement System. The panel was moderated by The Deal's senior editor of financial regulation, Ronald Orol.   Hudson Executive and Blue Harbour are among the firms that engage in what Orol describes as collaborative, constructivist-type activism, in which there are no threats of proxy contests.   Among Blue Harbour's investment criteria, said Robbins, is that "we have to want to back the management team." Robbins started Greenwich, Conn.-based Blue Harbour in 2004 after working at private equity firms such as General Atlantic Partners and KKR ( KKR) .    Both CalSTRS' Sheehan and BlackRock's Oleksiuk said they support activists that employ a variety of approaches.   "Any activist will tell you it's not their preferred approach," Sheehan said, referring to proxy battles. 



 



 










































